## Data Quality and Preparation Considerations

The following data preparation practices were applied before or during modeling:

- duplicate checks on key columns
- correction of data types
- standardization of category values such as Status and Purchase Process
- handling of blanks and unknown values
- validation of relationship cardinality
- review of filter paths to avoid ambiguity
- formatting of measures by business meaning

These steps were important to make the model both technically reliable and business-ready.

---

## User Experience Considerations

The data model was not designed only for technical correctness. It was also shaped to support a cleaner report experience.

Examples:
- hidden key columns to reduce clutter
- readable dimensions for slicers and visuals
- dedicated measure table for easier navigation
- relationship structure that supports natural filtering behavior

The goal is to help users focus on analysis rather than on the internal complexity of the model.

